segments.text: I think that our experiences that we had in relating ourselves to the schools of the state was very important.
What do you think before, say in the mid-50s,
or up until 1960, what do you think was the general scholastic impression of Texas A&M across the state?
What did the average counselor principal think A&M was?
I think that the average principal would say that Texas A&M College is a good college.
It has a good reputation.
But it is a military school and it does emphasize agriculture and engineering.
And I think that would be about it.
I had an idea about...
Well, Haskell, my going to A&M was a very fortunate thing for me.
I think it happened in that instance, and I doubt if it would happen again.
I happened to be into something that began to be a general movement in the country.
I thought, you know, if we did so well with these counselors on this initial book, handbook, why couldn't we bring counselors in in small groups and let them be a part of it?

My whole philosophy was that you determine your retention rate by what you do in terms of understanding the student, the placement of the student, the atmosphere in which they're handled, the characteristics of a good school.
So I went over to Buck Warris and I said, Buck, I need help.
And I told him what I would like to do.
And Buck and I agreed mutually that it was an excellent thing, but it had to be well organized.
we decided to call it the President's Conference for Scholars, I mean for, President's Conference for Freshman Students.
When we had the earlier conference, it was the President's Conference for Counselors.
And we thought that we would, this would be a conference
where the counselor would come, but we would not embarrass them.
They would observe and they would have help in any other way.
But we would make no attempt to do anything that would appear that we were trying to twist an arm or this sort of thing.
So we tied this in to this other movement
that we started out first.
Now there's a long history to this pastoral and it's documented in the, I'm sure in other areas.
We, well I took tests when I came here in the fall of 1934.
The old American Council on Education Psychological Examination was used in 1934 because I took it.
And I kept the records on it.
But when I left the center, and I was completely unaware of this, but Collison had a big house cleaning up there one weekend.
I know.
and destroyed all of the records.
It's a shame.
Let's go back to the early 60s.
What do you recall about the beginnings of what we would call the aspirations report and study that would end up with many meaningful recommendations?
How did that get generated?
Do you know?
How did that whole effort to have a self-study?
I don't know, but from my viewpoint over in the counseling center, I think that we owe a great deal to the Association of Farmer Students.
These were the people that emerged as leaders.

these were the people that could go back to Dallas or San Antonio and I remember that Buck and I worked on this and and Buck worked with the former students and you remember we had two former students an older one and a younger one at every high school in the state and
Haskell, that's awesome.
They would visit students.
They would have some recognition of counselors.
They would visit with counselors and say, we're here to help you.
I'll tell you what to do.
We're here to help you.
If you have a student who needs help, give us a chance.
This thing got so effective that, as I understand it, the university asked them to let up.
I don't remember the exact problem, but I did feel in the counseling center
that we began to gain a lot of sophistication.
I think our relationship with the college board was a very strategic need.
Describe how that came about.
That came about because the
The Association of Two-Year Colleges, as I understand it, used to meet on our campus every fall.
And for some reason we dropped the ball somewhere and it was picked up by you-know-who.
They agreed that every two-year college in the state would require
one or both of the two major testing, admission testing.
The College Board and the American College Testing Board.
Now, Mr. Heaton was courting the act.
For some reason, it got a Baptist 10 or something.
I don't know.
But Dean Hubert, again, was one of those quiet workers that did the best thing for the university, I think.
He said, now, Austin, I want this done in a way I don't have a lot of static.
I said, all right, I'll do it.
So my job was to work out a way to have the faculty make the decision of what the test would be.
Which test?
And so here's the way I did it.
I contact both of them.
I told them we would be happy for them to come.
and bring a representative or more and explain to us what our program was and, I mean, what their program was and how it would affect us.
Well, they did.
I was fortunate because the college board had sent their top people
a very pleasant fellow, but he simply was not effective in my opinion.
But our choosing the college board, Haskell was a very important move for us because we needed to get some descriptive
statements about the college that lent itself to quality.
And the college board represented quality and integrity.
They were a tremendous help to us.
They sent many people down here to, well, we even had, I put up the distress flag
it won't be history because I knew it was going to be hard to handle.
They sent a young lady in her late 30's I'd say, one of these sharpies from one of the eastern colleges
And it was great.
She handled Dr. Nance.
He wanted me to know.
He probably wouldn't have anything to do with it.
Well, before she left, he was.
Can I digress and tell you?
Oh, please do.
Please do.
Anyway.
Well, the achievement testing was an integral part of this.
I think that Dean Hubert was the first, but I think that Dr. Calhoun had some strong ideas because I worked with him on some of them.
We chose the credit by examination program would be much better if we had a standardized measure than to have handmade.
Because I think in most instances, if it's handmade, it has biases.
Well, we...
We developed this verifying code for loan credit by accumulation, used as kind of a model in lots of places.
But that was for placement.
But we were able to use some of the achievement tests for admission in other ways.
like honors classes, things of that nature.
Well, we were going to use the advanced placement test, and we didn't realize the level of expectancy on those tests.
there are not many fives made.
We finally ended up with, I believe, three or higher would get credit.
Now, this is a story about Dr. Nance.
Dr. Nance, he was still reluctant.
He had his own place.
So he, here comes our young lady again.
And she showed him one of the tests.
And boy, that thing was, it was something else.
Well, Dr. Nance, he looked it over carefully.
And he began to mellow quite a bit.
But he still, though, he wanted to give the test.
He said, fine.
He said, now, I want a staff member to be responsible to bring the test over to me, and I will give them.
And then he is to come back and get the test after I've scored it.
Well, he would send a pencil sheet back with the names of the students who failed.
Well, they would always say, this was when we were using his test.
they would all sign.
And then he would sign his name on the sheets or official.
Well, Elder Crow would come over and get the test from him.
Well, he brought him in, gave him to Hilda, and Hilda turned to one of the extra girls and said, type up.
this list here, and we had a little letter that we would mail and say, we thank you for participating.
And we worked on it so that you couldn't tell from the letter the size and all, whether you did or didn't, because they'd be handed out to the student.
Well, the next morning,
The phone rang early, and I answered it at the center.
And Dr. Nance said, early?
I said, yes, sir.
He said, I want to speak to that son of a bitch you have over there.
I said, Dr. Nance, you've got more than one.
Which one were you thinking about?
And oh, boy, he just exploded.
He said, they sent me one of these letters saying I couldn't even pass my own.
That's good.
I said, Dr. Nance, I'm afraid a problem has arisen here because the young lady that typed up the letters saw your name and she didn't know you were a very important person and she put you down.
And he said, well, you want to watch that?
I said, yes, sir.
We'll be alert on that from now on.
But he was a real character.
But I caught a lot of reading over that.
Haskell, I tell you, I felt like a counseling and testing center.
It should be a place where a student can go and seek help.
It should not be a center that tries to run things.
It's a service.
And y'all served the whole campus.
We served, well, President Rudder with his usual positiveness.
He said, Curly, I want you to help any
person who wants to attend this university.
I want you to help any person who's admitted and is a student.
And I want you to help any student that is preparing to leave.
I mean, is quitting.
And I want you to help any student who has graduated from here and is having problems.
I said, yes, sir.
That's what we will do.
Well, the Counseling Center today will not see a student if they are not fully enrolled.
See, they're thinking of money.
I never allowed that in to what we would do.
And I had a civil engineering
gradually come down from Dallas.
And he said, I can't work in this framework.
He said, when they're going to build something, they tell me to level it.
And he said, they have these beautiful trees and other landmarks.
And it's not necessary.
But he said, I'm young.
And I said, well, why don't you do it the other way?
Instead of using your engineering, go around to the out flank.
Talk to some architects.
And I'll bet you'll find that some of them are large enough, they want engineers on the staff.
Well, he was delighted, and sure enough, he got a job.
But I think President Lutter is right.
Now, during those years in the 60s, you worked with the associate and assistant deans of each of the colleges.
Describe those individuals.
Talk about each one of them as people.
Describe them.
Yes, we had a little, we called it a new student week committee.
I was chairman of that thing, and we got along fine.
We had a little problem during the Graff administration, but other than that,
This was a good organization.
I tried to coordinate what colleges wanted to do and I had this young man, Blakely, I think his name was, that came back here.
He bought into the McDonald things.
He was on the staff.
He was on
as his staff.
Blatchley.
Blatchley.
Ron Blatchley.
Fine young man.
And he seemed kind of at ease, not at ease.
And I said, what is the question you really have?
He said, well, they told me I had better watch myself with you.
He said, you're pretty hard on us.
And I said, how are you doing?
Oh, Ron said, oh, fine.
I said, well, you're not having much trouble, are you?
He said, no.
I said, well, I am very persistent in our recognizing and working with each other on what your area is.
But I have nothing to do with saying you can do this or you can't do this.
Now,
I had the fiscal office.
See, we had this thing finally to the point that we'd have a meeting of parents, and the fiscal office would send representatives to answer questions.
Well, the fellow who did that, he was a check, and he's dead now.
But he couldn't make it, so he sent this tall fellow, Smith.
And about noon, the phone rang and this major over in ROTC, he was at the same meeting, he said, you've got to fire that son of a bitch.
He said he got the audience so upset that one man got up to come up there.
I said, this fellow later worked in the restaurant.
I called and told them, oh, there's a check.
I said, you must not have him back.
We're not here for that.
We are here to serve as people that are glad to help.
Well, now all these members of this.
Yeah, these associate assistant deans.
New student committee.
But now, we had not only the associate dean, but we had people from the registrar's office.
Even Dollar got in on it.
Let's see.
Now, Dr. Ransdell was the person that... Now, Mike... Oh, the other one that was in engineering.
He's from my part of the country.
He's dead.
But Dr. Ransdell was, of course, a well-read person in this area because he was in on the very beginning of it and...
He was always prepared.
Dr. Potts was the dynamo.
Let's go.
That's what's holding us up.
That's R.C.
Potts in agriculture.
Yes.
R.C.
Potts told me one time, he said, Austin, you make me sick.
He said...
You run around here, and if things aren't working, you work on it.
And he said, that's not the way you do it.
He said, what you do is, if they want to goof off, let them goof off.
And then it'll get so bad that they'll say, we got to do something.
And then they will respond.
I said, well, now, Richard, we've got a lot of students here.
And they're having to pay for someone to learn the hard way.
And I don't want that.
The old sergeant from Beck Medicine, Mac Murray, he was in that famous march in Burma.
He was very blunt, very pragmatic,
but you could tell on him.
And he always made meetings.
Geology and science.
Yeah.
Well, no, John Beckham was in science.
And now John, John was a great man.
Great man.
Gifted.
His booming voice I can hear thinking about it.
Business?
Business.
We had this fellow that he was a pilot for World War II.
Tall.
But now he was very capable.
He lacked experience, but he, Lowe, Dan Lowe, Dan Lowe.
And the architecture, architecture, they were very intrigued with all this, but they had a little difficulty finding out where they, where they were.
One time I had the dean,
say, Olsen, what am I supposed to say?
And I said, well, just tell them that you welcomed me out to the campus, where you are, and you'll be glad to help.
It was a group of every one of them.
We didn't have a salary.
Let's see, we didn't do liberal arts.
In the liberal arts, let's see.
You know, these fellows played roles and... Schlesselman and then... Yeah, Schlesselman.
Then McCandless.
McCandless.
I think it was McCandless.
They, well you know McCandless had done a dozen things.
It was a very congenial group we worked for.
What about the man who ran the registrar's office for a few years named Heaton?
Describe Mr. Heaton and working with him.
Mr. Heaton was, to me, was an old time.
He was a man who had developed a certain procedure at work.
And he was not far changed.
As a matter of fact, when I introduced
the concept of the student being able to pay their fees while they're here.
Mr. Heaton says it's against the law.
And in some respects I felt for him because
It must have been many uncomfortable moments for him because Haskell was getting away from it.
And it would have been better if he had, Haskell, I just could not handle those two jobs.
I know I was supposed to have gone over there and cleaned that up, but I just honestly, well I was, my health was deteriorating.
And I know the last time I met with the president, he asked me if a certain plan was in agreement.
And I said, well, Mr. Heaton has agreed.
He said, I didn't ask Mr. Heaton, I asked you.
Well, you see, I felt like it.
